name: 3-n-propyl-2-pyrazolin-5-one

A simple pyrazole has a melting point around 68-70°C. The following features will affect the melting point: The presence of a n-propyl group adds a lipophilic alkyl chain, which typically increases the melting point due to increased molecular weight and van der Waals interactions; we can estimate this increase to be around +40°C. The ketone (C=O) group will participate in hydrogen bonding with proton donors and also increase the rigidity of the molecule; this might add around +25°C. The presence of the nitrogen atoms in the ring likely contributes through intermolecular hydrogen bonding or dipole-dipole interactions, which could add around +5-10°C. The combined 5-membered ring fused with a 4-membered ring adds strain and rigidity, which generally raises the melting point; this contribution might be around +15°C. The overall estimate will be a cumulative effect of these contributions.
Prediction: 68 (base pyrazole melting point) + 40 (n-propyl group) + 25 (ketone group) + 10 (nitrogen atoms in the ring) + 15 (ring strain and rigidity) = 158°C
